  "text": "The IκB negative-feedback loop constitutes the most prevalent and best understood mode of NF-κB regulation. Activation of NF-κB requires the degradation of the IκBs, allowing free NF-κB complexes to translocate to the nucleus. However, transcription of the NFΚBIA gene that encodes IκBα is induced immediately after NF-κB enters the nucleus and binds to its promoter. This generates newly synthesized IκBα that enters the nucleus, dissociates NF-κB from DNA, and escorts it back to the cytoplasm. Such a negative-feedback regulation was also revealed for IκΒβ and IκΒε, albeit with different kinetics of degradation and resynthesis [CITATION_1] . An oncoprotein known as p28",
